<paragraph pageId="57" pageNumber="606" type="mainText">
[32] 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:25263" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Anochetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Anochetus grandidieri Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="57" pageNumber="606" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grandidieri">Anochetus grandidieri</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="58" lastPageNumber="607" pageId="57" pageNumber="606" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="57" pageNumber="606" type="mainText">
The small African species related to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:25263" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Anochetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Anochetus grandidieri Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="57" pageNumber="606" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grandidieri">A. grandidieri</taxonomicName>
were multiplied mercilessly by Santschi and Bernard. These forms have short, stout mandibles and small, but not minute eyes (worker 
<traitTerm normTerm="maximum diameter of the compound eye" termSource="HAO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HAO_0002326">EL</traitTerm>
0.07-0.12 mm), and the antennal scapes usually fail to 
<normalizedToken originalValue="réach" pageId="57" pageNumber="606">
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000029">reach</traitTerm>
</normalizedToken>
the posterior corners of the 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000305">
<traitTerm normTerm="head" termSource="HAO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HAO_0000397">head</traitTerm>
</traitTerm>
; funicular segments II, III, IV short, hardly longer than 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000020">broad</traitTerm>
. The petiolar node is narrow in 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00002000">side</traitTerm>
view and tapered apicad to a sharp, or at least very narrow apex; in front view, the petiolar 
<traitTerm normTerm="margin" termSource="HAO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HAO_0000510">margin</traitTerm>
varies from convex to emarginate, and is often merely flattened in the middle. The 
<traitTerm normTerm="vertex" termSource="HAO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HAO_0001077">vertex</traitTerm>
, 
<traitTerm normTerm="pronotal disc" termSource="HAO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HAO_0001702">pronotal disc</traitTerm>
and gastric 
<traitTerm normTerm="dorsum" termSource="HAO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HAO_0000281">dorsum</traitTerm>
are mostly smooth and shining, with spaced punctures of varying coarseness.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="57" pageNumber="606" type="mainText">
Only in 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:25263" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Anochetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Anochetus grandidieri Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="57" pageNumber="606" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grandidieri">A. grandidieri</taxonomicName>
of Madagascar do the frontal striae 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000029">reach</traitTerm>
far back on the 
<traitTerm normTerm="vertex" termSource="HAO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HAO_0001077">vertex</traitTerm>
, where they overrun some of the punctures and surround the front and sides of the posteromedian 
<traitTerm normTerm="impression" termSource="HAO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HAO_0000417">impression</traitTerm>
. This is the commonly-collected small 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2346" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Anochetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Anochetus Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="57" pageNumber="606" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Anochetus</taxonomicName>
of Madagascar in leaf litter and 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00002261">forest soil</traitTerm>
, including the 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00001998">soil</traitTerm>
about the roots of epiphytes: 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Andasibé" pageId="57" pageNumber="606">Andasibe</normalizedToken>
(= 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Périnet" pageId="57" pageNumber="606">Perinet</normalizedToken>
), 950-980 mm, several collections in 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000111">forest</traitTerm>
, March 1969 and February 1977; W. L. and D. E. Brown; Imerintsiatosika, about 34 km W of Tananarive, 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000266">pasture</traitTerm>
with eucalyptus, W. L. Brown; above Sakaramy on 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000064">road</traitTerm>
to Joffreville, 500 m, litter of disturbed 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000111">forest</traitTerm>
, Browns; 84 km SW Sambava on 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000064">road</traitTerm>
to Andapa, disturbed 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000111">forest</traitTerm>
, Browns. 8 km W of Maroantsetra, degraded 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000111">forest</traitTerm>
with vanilla, Browns.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="57" pageNumber="606" type="mainText">
M. A. Peyrieras has found this species in 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000111">forest</traitTerm>
litter and 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01000000">humus</traitTerm>
berlesates from: Causse de Kelifely, west-central Madagascar, litter of dry 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00002053">limestone</traitTerm>
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000111">forest</traitTerm>
; route 
<normalizedToken originalValue="d’Anosibé" pageId="57" pageNumber="606">d'Anosibe</normalizedToken>
(from Moramanga); Beforona, 500 m.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="57" pageNumber="606" type="mainText">
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:133661" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Anochetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" httpURI="http://treatment.plazi.org/id/1B6CA0F7C3C39B434332611E19FBAE72" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Anochetus madecassus Santschi" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="57" pageNumber="606" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="madecassus">A. madecassus</taxonomicName>
is just the queen of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:25263" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Anochetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Anochetus grandidieri Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="57" pageNumber="606" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grandidieri">grandidieri</taxonomicName>
. The only other 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2346" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Anochetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Anochetus Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="57" pageNumber="606" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Anochetus</taxonomicName>
at present known from Madagascar is 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:25279" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Anochetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Anochetus madagascarensis Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="57" pageNumber="606" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="madagascarensis">A. madagascarensis</taxonomicName>
[29], also represented by repeated collections.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="57" pageNumber="606" type="mainText">
On the African mainland, the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:25263" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Anochetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Anochetus grandidieri Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="57" pageNumber="606" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grandidieri">grandidieri</taxonomicName>
complex groups into two entities that differ by minor, but possibly constant characters. One of these entities occurs in the eastern 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000305">Cape</traitTerm>
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000104">Province</traitTerm>
of South Africa, where it corresponds to the type of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:25303" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Anochetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Anochetus punctaticeps Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="57" pageNumber="606" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctaticeps">A. punctaticeps</taxonomicName>
, the first name available for it. This form is concolorous ferruginous yellow and has a smooth and shining first gastric 
<traitTerm normTerm="tergum" termSource="HAO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HAO_0001006">tergum</traitTerm>
, with only fine and inconspicuous punctures; the propodeal angles are low and obtuse, and the petiolar node as seen from the 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00002000">side</traitTerm>
tapers to a narrowly-rounded apex (fig. 20). The type locality of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:25303" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Anochetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Anochetus punctaticeps Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="57" pageNumber="606" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctaticeps">A. punctaticeps</taxonomicName>
is Port Elizabeth, eastern 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000305">Cape</traitTerm>
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000104">Province</traitTerm>
. I took samples at Walmer, a western suburb of Port Elizabeth, in thin eucalypt litter along a roadside strip; at Alexandria 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000111">Forest</traitTerm>
, near Alexandria; at 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Beggar’s" pageId="57" pageNumber="606">Beggar's</normalizedToken>
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000176">Bush</traitTerm>
, near Grahamstown, in 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000029">ravine</traitTerm>
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000111">forest</traitTerm>
; and on Signal 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000083">Hill</traitTerm>
, near Grahamstown, under a 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00001995">rock</traitTerm>
in thin 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000111">forest</traitTerm>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="58" pageNumber="607" type="mainText">
<pageBreakToken pageId="58" pageNumber="607" start="start">In</pageBreakToken>
eastern, central and western sub-Saharan Africa, panctaticeps is replaced by a rather common, more variable form, corresponding to a group of available names, the earliest of which is 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:133679" authorityName="Forel" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Anochetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Anochetus grandidieri var. katonae Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="607" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="grandidieri" variety="katonae">
A. grandidieri var. katonae 
<authority pageId="58" pageNumber="607">Forel</authority>
</taxonomicName>
1907, so that I am calling the species 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:25273" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Anochetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Anochetus katonae Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="607" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="katonae">A. katonae</taxonomicName>
. The types of the worker-based species and varieties concinms, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:133678" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Anochetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Anochetus punctatus Santschi" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="607" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctatus">punctatus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:133676" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Anochetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Anochetus punctatus var. occidentalis Santschi" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="607" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="punctatus" variety="occidentalis">punctatus var. occidentalis</taxonomicName>
, lampttei and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:133673" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Anochetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Anochetus gnomulus Bernard" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="607" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gnomulus">gnomulus</taxonomicName>
all seem to be minor variants of this same species. The type of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:133677" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Anochetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Anochetus parvus Santschi" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="607" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parvus">A. parvus</taxonomicName>
is missing from its 
<traitTerm termSource="ENVO" termUri="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00000477">mount</traitTerm>
and presumably lost, but there is nothing about its description to suggest that it belongs to a different species. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:133675" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Anochetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Anochetus parvus var. longiceps Santschi" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="607" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="parvus" variety="longiceps">A. parvus var. longiceps</taxonomicName>
is based partly on a queen from Cameroun, so I cannot be sure that it is not one of the species with minute worker eyes, such as 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:25313" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Anochetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Anochetus siphneus Brown" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="607" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="siphneus">siphneus</taxonomicName>
, but in the absence of queen samples of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:25313" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Anochetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Anochetus siphneus Brown" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="607" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="siphneus">siphneus</taxonomicName>
there appears to be no way to decide this problem; I am provisionally listing 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:224389" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Anochetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Anochetus longiceps Santschi" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="607" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longiceps">longiceps</taxonomicName>
as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:25273" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Anochetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Anochetus katonae Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="607" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="katonae">katonae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
